Does publication bias (QRP) mess up are moderators miss estimated? If yes can we get better estimates by applying adjustments?

Meta Analysis

This simulation study tests: 1. How publication bias affects ability to detect moderators in meta-analysis 2. Whether adjustments for publication bias may improve or impair detection of moderators, given publication bias.

Data are simulated according to two scenarios: Medium effects: Studies have true effects of 0, 0.3, or 0.6 Small effects: Studies have true effects of 0, 0.2, or 0.4 Data are then subjected to publication bias and QRPs No bias: All study results are reported Biased: Only 20% of of nonsignificant results are published. 50% of studies involve aggressive p-hacking, 40% use moderate p-hacking. Number of studies per group is fixed to k = 20 Studies have sample size of minimum 20/cell, maximum 200/cell, average 50/cell.

Analysis

Nave analysis: Meta-analysis tests the moderator effect without adjustment for publication bias WLS-MRA (single slope): Meta-analysis tests the moderator effect after PET adjustment for publication bias. PET slope is fixed across groups. WLS-MRA (variable slope): Meta-analysis tests the moderator effect after PET adjustment for publication bias. PET slope may vary across groups. Results are presented in terms of bias, root mean squared error, and Type I/II error.

Set-up?

Theme set-up

Medium effects

Group Means: 0, 0.3, 0.6 Publication bias causes overestimation of = 0 and underestimation of mods. This underestimation causes increased Type II error rates for moderators. PET-RMA does not quite undo this bias and can have poor power and efficiency.

Small Effects

Group means: 0, 0.2, 0.4 When effects are smaller, the loss of power is more pronounced. Again, PET-RMA does not fix the biases and can inflict further loss of efficiency.
